What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 customers with 81 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in my dataset are:

  • LoanStatus: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.
  • BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  • EmoloymentStatus: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.
  • ProsperRating: The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • ProsperScore: A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  • StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  • Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner: A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My aim for this project is to investigate the factors that impact the borrowers APR. I will use the variables selected above to generate insights to come to a conclusion. My expectation is that the amount given to the borrowers is part of the determinant, however, i am going to explore other variables.

# Since there's a long tail in the distribution, i'll put it on a log scale instead
log_binsize = 0.05
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(df_sub['StatedMonthlyIncome'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df_sub, x = 'StatedMonthlyIncome', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4, 5e4], [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k', '20k', '50k'])
plt.xlabel('Monthly Income ($)')
plt.title('Distribution of stated monthly income')
plt.show();

Insight¶

  • The distribution of the stated monthly income shows that majority of the monthly income is less than 10000. The distribution is alos right skewed with a long tail. I put it on a log scale, the log transformation essentially reels these values into the center of the distribution making it look more like a Normal distribution. This transformation shows clearly the highest peak is around the 5k mark, and most borrowers earn between 3k and 8k.
  • Next up, I will explore the employment status column.

The distribution of the Borrowers APR appears to be multimodal with varying peaks across the distribution. However, the point with the highest peak is 0.36%, which means that majority of the borrowers APR is 0.36. # plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.
# can use a larger sample since there are fewer plots and they're simpler in nature.
def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loans_samp, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], x_vars = cat_variables,

In the boxgrids above, it appears that there are some negative relationships between the categorical variables and the two numeric variables used for comparison, i.e., BorrowerAPR, and LoanOriginalAmount. The borrowers associated with high risks were given the least amount in loans and higher APR. While the borrowers with the least risk got higher amount in loans and lower APR. The relationship between the LoanOriginalAmount and the term reveals that there is a progression inthe term based on the amount given in loans, this means that small amounts were given to the people with a 12 months term, and as the term increases the amount increases, however, there are some exceptions. Employed borrowers, self-employed borrowers, borrowers whose employment status was categorized under others, and full-time borrowers got higher loan amounts that part-time, and unemployed borrowers.
